<TITLE> Stocks close down </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 20 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks closed down for a fourth day Wednesday, with the DSE also witnessing a decrease in turnover as investors sold off holdings at lower margins to buy shares, according to market observers. "As the merchant banks are being overcautious about issuing loans, investors are having to sell off shares at lower prices to buy new issues, which has impacted the turnover," said Salahuddin Ahmed, chief executive of Dhaka Stock Exchange. The DSE's general index marked falls at the start of the trading day, gained sharply during the second hour only to slump again in the third hour, remaining before rising slightly toward close of trade. The benchmark DGEN or general index fell 23.83 points or 0.83 percent to close at 2840.21. The DSI or all share price index finished at 2400.97, up 15.19 points or 0.62 percent. The DSE-20 blue chip index gained 11.30 points or 0.49 percent to close at 2294.87. Turnover on the country's prime bourse continued to fall, totalling Tk 1.27 billion, compared to Tuesday's Tk 1.30 billion from the trading of 8,345,380 shares. Of the traded issues,128 advanced, 86 declined and sixteen issues held steady. The day witnessed power shares falling as well as mutual funds, after their gains in recent days. Banks and state run oil entities made a come back Wednesday with their prices increasing mainly due to buying pressure. Summit Power topped the turnover board closing at Tk 950.25, down 39.26 percent. AB Bank followed to finish 0.23 percent up at Tk 2792.75. Grameen Mutual Fund One fell 1.06 percent to Tk 120.80. State-run Jamuna Oil finished 0.91 percent up at Tk 309.50. Meghna Petroleum crept up 0.88 percent to Tk 306.60. Among the other active scrips, UCBL, BRAC Bank and Prime Bank also gained, while IDLC and DESCO fell. Chittagong stocks closed upbeat Wednesday with all indices gaining and sectors closing mixed. Miscellaneous and services & property gained the most ,while ICT and leather & footwear suffered the biggest declines. The CSCX or selective category index rose 7.89 points or 0.16 percent to 4690.99. The CASPI or all share price index closed at 7326, up 22.50 points or 0.30 percent. The bourse's blue chip CSE-30 finished up 19.04 points or 0.29 percent at 657.80. Turnover amounted to Tk 233.60 million from 1,877,252 traded shares. Gainers beat losers 67 to 53 with eleven issues remaining unchanged. bdn
